If you’re curious about the future of American conservatism, a good person to consider might be Ben Shapiro.
Regardless of your politics, it’s easy to understand Shapiro’s appeal—he’s intelligent, collected, and consistent.
His new book, The Right Side of History, was released in mid-March and soon landed on The New York Times best sellers list.
But, as a writer, at least in The Right Side of History, he’s vague, dull, and self-contradictory.
There are hints of an interesting argument scattered throughout The Right Side of History, but they sit in logical isolation.